<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1873-12-01T23:55:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-12-31T23:56:00-05:00" n="213" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d213">
                                    <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-chapter-head">[Hamburg]</head>
                                    <opener>
                                        <dateline rendition="#right">[<date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-volume-rules" calendar="gregorian" notAfter="1873-12-01T23:59:59-04:56" notBefore="1873-01-01T00:00:00-04:56">undated</date>.]</dateline>
                                    </opener>
                                    <p>Aliens can become naturalized after six months’ residence on
                                        payment of a small fee. The law of Hamburg is said to
                                        recognize a double allegiance in persons thus, naturalized,
                                        and does not require any renunciation of native
                                            allegiance.<note n="1" xml:id="d213fn1">Aliens
                                            Committee, <ref target="frus1873p1v1#pg_59">p.
                                            59</ref>.</note></p>
                                </div>
                            </body></text></TEI>